{"id":"2109.05950","submitter":"Guillem Mart\\'i-Devesa","authors":"G. Mart\\'i-Devesa and O. Reimer","title":"Eta Carinae with Fermi-LAT: Two full orbits and the third periastron","comments":"8 pages, 8 figures, 3 tables. Accepted for publication in Astronomy\n  and Astrophysics","journal-ref":"A&A 654, A44 (2021)","doi":"10.1051/0004-6361/202140451","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.HE astro-ph.SR","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Context. Colliding-wind binaries are massive stellar systems featuring\nstrong, interacting winds. These binaries may be actual particle accelerators,\nmaking them variable gamma-ray sources due to changes in the wind collision\nregion along the orbit. However, only two of these massive stellar binary\nsystems have been identified as high-energy sources. The first and archetypical\nsystem of this class is Eta Carinae, a bright gamma-ray source with orbital\nvariability peaking around its periastron passage. Aims. The origin of the high\nenergy emission in Eta Carinae is still unclear, with both lepto-hadronic and\nhadronic scenarios being under discussion. Moreover, the gamma-ray emission\nseemed to differ between the two periastrons previously observed with the Fermi\nLarge Area Telescope. Continuing observations might provide highly valuable\ninformation for the understanding of the emission mechanisms in this system.\nMethods. We have used almost 12 years of data from the Fermi Large Area\nTelescope. We studied both low and high energy components, searching for\ndifferences and similarities between both orbits, and made use of this large\ndataset to search for emission from nearby colliding-wind binaries. Results. We\nshow how the energy component above 10 GeV of Eta Carinae peaks months before\nthe 2014 periastron, while the 2020 periastron is the brightest to date.\nAdditionally, upper limits are provided for the high-energy emission in other\nparticle-accelerating colliding-wind systems. Conclusions. Current gamma-ray\nobservations of Eta Carinae strongly suggest that the wind collision region of\nthis system is perturbed from orbit to orbit affecting particle transport\nwithin the shock.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 13 Sep 2021 13:25:39 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-10-13"}
