{"id":"2110.00384","submitter":"Martin Charron","authors":"Martin Charron and Ayrton Zadra","title":"Addendum: Hidden symmetries, trivial conservation laws and Casimir\n  invariants in geophysical fluid dynamics (2018 J. Phys. Commun. 2 115018)","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  An extension is proposed to the internal symmetry transformations associated\nwith mass, entropy and other Clebsch-related conservation in geophysical fluid\ndynamics. Those symmetry transformations were previously parameterized with an\narbitrary function $\\cal F$ of materially conserved Clebsch potentials. The\nextension consists in adding potential vorticity $q$ to the list of fields on\nwhich a new arbitrary function $\\cal G$ depends. If ${\\cal G}=q{\\cal A}(s)$,\nwhere ${\\cal A}(s)$ is an arbitrary function of specific entropy $s$, then the\nsymmetry is trivial and gives rise to a trivial conservation law. Otherwise,\nthe symmetry is non-trivial and an associated non-trivial conservation law\nexists. Moreover, the notions of trivial and non-trivial Casimir invariants are\ndefined. All non-trivial symmetries that become hidden following a reduction of\nphase space are associated with non-trivial Casimir invariants of a\nnon-canonical Hamiltonian formulation for fluids, while all trivial\nconservation laws are associated with trivial Casimir invariants.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 12 Sep 2021 21:19:36 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 4 Oct 2021 01:00:56 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 13 Oct 2021 11:56:23 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-10-14"}
